in-group. The Stoners enjoyed their days lounging, chatting, and making crafts, while the Traders—through a complex market of playing cards—competed for the highest bankrolls. When they came into contact, misunderstanding, competition, and even manipulation prevailed, to the point that each group became so convinced of its own superiority that even after the simulation’s end the students could not reconcile. Throughout her riveting narrative, Downing Wilson interweaves fascinating discussions on the importance of play, emotions, and intergroup interaction in the formation and maintenance of group identities, as well as on the dynamic social processes at work when different cultural groups interact. A fascinating account of social experimentation, the book paints a vivid portrait of our deepest social tendencies and the powers they have over how we make friends and enemies alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCultural relationsvCross-cultural studies. 0aCultural relations-Cross-cultural studies. 0aGroup identityvCross-cultural studies. 0aGroup identity-Cross-cultural studies. 0aIntergroup relationsvCross-cultural studies. 0aIntergroup relations-Cross-cultural studies. 0aPsychology, Experimental. 0aSocial interactionvCross-cultural studies. 0aSocial interaction-Cross-cultural studies. 0aSocial psychologyxMethodology. 0aSocial psychology-Methodology. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  acultural difference, group identity, endogamy, exogamy, communication, society, competition, superiority, hierarchy, authority, misunderstanding, manipulation, simulation, play, emotions, intergroup interaction, social experimentation, psychology, nonfiction, methodology, research, boundaries, collaboration, markets, ideology, separation, irreconcilable, community.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter